# Cursor Rules

## File Edit Restrictions

**DO NOT edit the following file types directly - they are managed by IDEs and can be corrupted:**

- `.storyboard` files - Use Xcode Interface Builder
- `.xcodeproj` files - Use Xcode project editor
- `.xcworkspace` files - Use Xcode workspace editor
- `.lproj` files - Use Xcode localization editor
- `.pbxproj` files - Use Xcode project editor
- `.xcscheme` files - Use Xcode scheme editor
- `.xcuserdata` files - User-specific Xcode data

**If you need to modify these files, instruct the user to make changes in the appropriate IDE (Xcode, etc.) instead of editing them directly.**

## Safe File Types to Edit

You may edit these file types directly:
- `.h`, `.m` (Objective-C source files)
- `.swift` (Swift source files)
- `.js`, `.ts` (JavaScript/TypeScript)
- `.json` (JSON configuration files)
- `.md` (Markdown documentation)
- `.html`, `.css` (Web files)
- `.sh` (Shell scripts)
- `.conf`, `.config` (Configuration files)
- `.txt` (Text files)
- `.py`, `.rb`, etc. (Other source files)

## Apple TV Development Guidelines

If working with Apple TV (tvOS) applications:
- Use UIAlertController for text input on tvOS (UITextField doesn't work properly)
- Always use gesture recognizers for text field interaction
- Never edit `.storyboard` files directly - use Xcode Interface Builder

## General Guidelines

- Always ask before editing IDE-managed files
- Prefer source code files (`.h`, `.m`, `.swift`, `.js`, etc.)
- When in doubt, suggest using the appropriate IDE tool

